    label "articulo::285::Deep learning-based attenuation correction in brain PET studies"
    tipo "articulo"
    nombre "Deep learning-based attenuation correction in brain PET studies"
    indice "285"
    Year "2025"
    ISBN "978-0-7354-5302-9"
    ISSN "1551-7616, 0094-243X"
    Doi "10.1063/5.0308436"
    URL "https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105027737494?origin=resultslist"
    Area "SIAV"
    Abstract "A dataset comprising human brain PET studies reconstructed with and without attenuation correction (AC) was utilized to train a deep learning framework tailored for AC. The uncorrected reconstructions served as the input while the corrected recon-structions functioned as ground truth (target). The implemented deep learning architectures encompassed U-Net, Residual U-Net, Attention U-Net, Residual Attention U-Net and Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs). The performance of the trained models was assessed via the Structural Similarity Index Measure (SSIM) computed between the model predictions and the ground truth data. The best results were achieved with a U-Net architecture, yielding corrected studies with a mean SSIM value of 0.995 in comparison to the ground truth. Furthermore, the application of a trained U-Net enables the correction of a complete study within approximately 3 seconds, which is a clinically acceptable time."
  ]
